{"title_page": "Ruel (singer)", "text_new": "{{Dutch name|van Dijk|Dijk}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Ruel\n| image            = Ruel (44766536300).jpg\n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = yes\n| background       = solo_singer  <!-- mandatory format: please do not change or remove -->\n| caption          = Ruel performing at the Byron Bay Falls Festival 2018\n| birth_name       = Ruel Vincent Van Dijk\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|2002|10|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Isleworth]], [[London]], United Kingdom\n| origin           = [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]], Australia\n| instruments      = {{hlist|Guitar|Piano|}}\n| genre            = {{hlist||[[Soul music|Soul]]|[[Alternative rock|Alternative pop]]|R&B}}\n| occupations      = Singer-songwriter\n| years_active     = 2017\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|The Muziek Trust|[[RCA Records|RCA]]|[[Sony Music Australia]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[M-Phazes]]|[[Dylan Joel]]|[[Billie Eilish]]|[[SG Lewis]]|[[Shawn Mendes]]}}\n| website          = https://www.oneruel.com/\n| height           = 193cm\n}}\n\n'''Ruel Vincent van Dijk''' (born 29 October 2002),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/ruel-mn0001646575/biography|title=Ruel Biography|publisher=All Music|author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|accessdate=12 January 2019}}</ref> known [[mononym]]ously as '''Ruel''' (pronounced \"Rool\", after the Dutch name \"Roel\", short version of \"Roelof\"), is an English born Australian singer-songwriter from [[Sydney]], best known for his singles \"[[Don't Tell Me (Ruel song)|Don't Tell Me]]\" and \"[[Younger (Ruel song)|Younger]]\". At the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2018]] he won the award for [[ARIA Award for Breakthrough Artist \u2013 Release|Breakthrough Artist]] for his single \"[[Dazed & Confused (Ruel song)|Dazed & Confused]] He is in a relationship with Maria Paz Agudelo\".\n\n==Early life==\nRuel van Dijk was born on October 29, 2002, in Isleworth, London, to British mother, Kate van Dijk, and Dutch-born and New Zealand-raised father, Ralph van Dijk.<ref name=\" SMH\" >{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/music/a-ruel-twist-of-fate-and-a-schoolboy-soul-singer-is-on-his-way-20180702-p4zoy2.html|title=A Ruel twist of fate and a schoolboy soul singer is on his way|first=Andrew|last=Drever|publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald|date=2 July 2018|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref> His father is the founder of Australian radio agency, ''Eardrum''.<ref>https://au.linkedin.com/in/ralph-van-dijk-b947257</ref> He has two sisters, Sylvie and Stella \u201cCoco\u201d.\n\n==Music career==\n===2015\u20132017: Early years===\n\nIn 2015, Ruel's father sent a demo of him singing [[James Bay (singer)|James Bay]]'s \"[[Let It Go (James Bay song)|Let It Go]]\" to [[Grammy Awards|Grammy Award-winning]] producer [[M-Phazes]]. M-Phazes said, \"I lost my mind when I heard his voice!\"<ref name=\"SMH\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2017/07/14/exclusive-go-behind-the-scenes-with-ruel-and-m-phazes-on-their-new-track,-dont-tell-me/|title= EXCLUSIVE: Go Behind The Scenes With Ruel & M-Phazes On Their New Track, 'Don't Tell Me'|publisher=The Music|date=13 July 2017|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Ruel released his debut single \"[[Golden Years (Ruel and M-Phazes song)|Golden Years]]\" with M-Phazes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/entertainment/confidential/and-ruel-releases-debut-single-golden-years/news-story/5c0625e666734efbb32b02cc19828d81|title= Ruel releases debut single Golden Years|publisher=[[Herald Sun]]|date=17 April 2017 |accessdate=20 August 2017}}</ref> In June, Ruel made his live radio debut performing [[Jack Garratt]]'s \"Weathered\" on [[triple J]]'s [[Like a Version]]. At 14, he was the youngest-ever featured performer on the segment{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}. The video gathered half a million video views in less than 48 hours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.umusicpub.com/au/Artists/R/Ruel.aspx|title=Ruel (artists) |publisher= Universal Music Publishing Group|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Ruel released \"[[Don't Tell Me (Ruel song)|Don't Tell Me]]\", which peaked at number 86 on the [[ARIA Chart]]. Later in September, [[Elton John]] played \"Don't Tell Me\" on [[BBC Radio 1]], giving Ruel high praise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themusic.com.au/news/all/2017/11/22/elton-john-continues-to-praise-sydney-artist-ruel-you-have-the-most-amazing-voice/|title= Elton John Continues To Praise Sydney Artist Ruel: 'You Have The Most Amazing Voice'|publisher=The Music|date=22 November 2017|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref>  The track was also featured in CelebMix's 21 songs by under-21s in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://celebmix.com/celebmixs-21-songs-by-under-21s/|title= CelebMix\u2019s 21 Songs by Under-21s|publisher=CelebMix.com|date=30 November 2017|accessdate=7 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn November, Ruel joined [[Khalid (singer)|Khalid]] on his American Teen Tour of Australia and New Zealand. Later that month, Ruel signed with [[RCA Records]] internationally. In December, Tom Thum released a cover of [[Rag'n'Bone Man]]'s \"[[Human (Rag'n'Bone Man song)|Human]]\" featuring Ruel on vocals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/human-feat-ruel/1319641874?i=1319641884 |title= Human (featuring Ruel)|publisher=iTunes Australia|accessdate=4 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2018\u2013present: ''Ready'' and ''Free Time'' EPs===\nOn 24 March 2018, Ruel played at Pop Spring Festival, [[Tokyo]], where he did his first meet and greet. On 4 April, Ruel performed at the [[2018 Commonwealth Games opening ceremony|Opening Ceremony]] of the [[2018 Commonwealth Games]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/sport/commonwealth-games/live-coverage-of-the-2018-commonwealth-games-opening-ceremony-on-the-gold-coast/news-story/d20d3ed254dbef79ad9abaf2e29e244e|title=Gold Coast dazzles on the world stage as Commonwealth Games are officially opened |publisher=[[news.com.au]]|date= 5 October 2018|accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref> On 19 April, a music video for the single \"Don't Tell Me\" was released.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eE48SVjGMUc|title=Ruel - Don't Tell Me (Official Video)|via=YouTube|date=19 April 2018|access-date=8 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 June, Ruel announced the release of his debut [[extended play]] ''[[Ready (Ruel EP)|Ready]]'' on 15 June, as well as a headline tour in June and July.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amnplify.com.au/ruel-reveals-official-video-for-dazed-and-confused/|title=Ruel reveals official video for \u2018Dazed & Confused\u2019 first ever solo headline shows this June and July, pre-order Ruel's debut EP Ready, set for release June 15 |publisher=amnplify|date=2 June 2018|accessdate=5 June 2018}}</ref> In October, Ruel performed to a sell-out crowd in Sydney, and received the news that his single \"[[Younger (Ruel song)|Younger]]\" had recently been certified Gold by ARIA. On 11 October, Ruel was nominated for the Breakout Artist award for the [[ARIA Music Awards of 2018|ARIA Awards]], which he later won.\n\nOn 10 January 2019, Ruel was confirmed to appear on [[Hilltop Hoods]]' new album ''[[The Great Expanse]]'', on the track \"Fire & Grace\". The album was then released on 22 February.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/hilltop-hoods-new-album-tracklist-illy-ecca-vandal-timberwolf/10705834 |title=Hilltop Hoods just dropped the tracklist for their feature-packed new album |publisher=ABC |work=Triple J |date=10 January 2019 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |author=Newstead, Al}}</ref> On 1 May, Ruel released the lead single from his ''[[Free Time (EP)|Free Time]]'' EP, \"[[Painkiller (Ruel song)|Painkiller]]\", alongside an accompanying music video.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://themusicnetwork.com/sotd-ruel-sets-the-tone-for-next-ep-with-painkiller/ |title=SOTD: Ruel sets the tone for next EP with \u2018Painkiller\u2019 |publisher=The Music Network |date=1 May 2019 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |author=Staff Writer}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dTwj7PhpY9M|title=Ruel - Painkiller (Official Video)|author=Ruel |date=1 May 2019 |accessdate=2 May 2019 |via=YouTube}}</ref> On 9 August, saw Ruel released the single \"[[Face to Face (Ruel song)|Face to Face]]\" alongside a music video, which was shot while Ruel was on tour in France. On 13 September, Ruel released his second EP, ''Free Time''. In November 2019, Ruel was an opening act for two shows of [[Shawn Mendes: The Tour]].\n\n==Discography==\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\" border=\"1\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:14em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[ARIA Charts|AUS]]<br /><ref name=\"AUS\">Peaks in Australia:\n* \"Don't Tell Me\": {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2017/08/aria-chart-watch-434/|title=ARIA Chart Watch 434|publisher=auspOp|date=19 August 2017|accessdate=20 August 2017}}\n* \"Dazed & Confused\": {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2018/6/aria-chart-watch-477/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #477|publisher=auspOp|date=16 June 2018|accessdate=16 June 2018}}\n* ''Ready'': {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2018/6/aria-chart-watch-478/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #478|publisher=auspOp|date=23 June 2018|accessdate=23 June 2018}}\n* \"Younger\": {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2018/7/aria-chart-watch-481/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #481|publisher=auspOp|date=14 July 2018|accessdate=14 July 2018}}\n* \"Painkiller\": {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2019/06/aria-chart-watch-529/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #529|publisher=auspOp|date=15 June 2019|accessdate=18 July 2019}}\n* \"Face to Face\": {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2019/08/aria-chart-watch-538/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #538|publisher=auspOp|date=17 August 2019|accessdate=17 August 2019}}\n* \"Real Thing\": {{cite web|url=https://www.auspop.com.au/2019/09/aria-chart-watch-543/|title=ARIA Chart Watch #543|publisher=auspOp|date=21 September 2019|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ]]<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4752|title=NZ Top 40 Albums Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=23 September 2019|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Ready (Ruel EP)|Ready]]''\n|\n* Released: 15 June 2018\n* Formats: [[Music download|Digital download]], [[Media streaming|streaming]]\n* Label: [[RCA Records|RCA]], [[Sony Music Australia]]\n| 76 || \u2014{{efn|group=upper-alpha|''Ready'' did not enter the [[Official New Zealand Music Chart|NZ Top 40 Albums Chart]], but peaked at number 3 on the Heatseeker Albums Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nztop40.co.nz/chart/albums?chart=4493|title=NZ Heatseeker Albums Chart|publisher=[[Recorded Music NZ]]|date=25 June 2018|accessdate=22 June 2018}}</ref>}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[Free Time (EP)|Free Time]]''\n|\n* Released: 13 September 2019<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc.net.au/triplej/news/musicnews/ruel-announces-new-ep-and-all-ages-free-time-tour/11367974 |title=Ruel announces new EP and all ages Free Time tour |work=ABC |date=31 July 2019 |accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n* Formats: Digital download, streaming\n* Label: RCA, Sony Music Australia\n| 3<br /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/albums-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Albums|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=23 September 2019|accessdate=21 September 2019}}</ref> || 18\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n====As lead artist====\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=text-align:center;\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Ti