g/nuke/ nuclear weapons] and their [https://web.archive.org/web/20150329105730/http://fas.org/nuke/intro/nuke/effects.htm effects]\n* [http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/intro/a-bomb.htm Globalsecurity.org] provides a well-written primer in nuclear weapons design concepts (site navigation on righthand side).\n* [http://nuclearweaponarchive.org/Library/Teller.html More information on the design of two-stage fusion bombs]\n* [https://fas.org/irp/threat/mctl98-2/mctl98-2.pdf Militarily Critical Technologies List (MCTL), Part II (1998)] (PDF) from the US Department of Defense at the Federation of American Scientists website.\n* [https://fas.org/sgp/othergov/doe/rdd-7.html \"Restricted Data Declassification Decisions from 1946 until Present\"], Department of Energy report series published from 1994 until January 2001 which lists all known declassification actions and their dates. Hosted by Federation of American Scientists.\n* [https://fas.org/sgp/eprint/morland.html The Holocaust Bomb: A Question of Time] is an update of the 1979 court case ''USA v. The Progressive'', with links to supporting documents on nuclear weapon design.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080226054314/http://alsos.wlu.edu/qsearch.aspx?browse=science%2FNuclear+Weapons+Design Annotated bibliography on nuclear weapons design from the Alsos Digital Library for Nuclear Issues]\n* [http://www.wilsoncenter.org/nuclear-history-documents/ The Woodrow Wilson Center's Nuclear Proliferation International History Project] or NPIHP is a global network of individuals and institutions engaged in the study of international nuclear history through archival documents, oral history interviews and other empirical sources.\n\n{{Nuclear technology}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nuclear Weapon Design}}\n[[Category:Nuclear weapons|Design]]\n[[Category:Nuclear weapon design| ]]\n[[Category:Weapon design]]\n", "name_user": "103.255.5.72", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_weapon_design"}
{"title_page": "Tori Allen-Martin", "text_new": "{{dablinks|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|British actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR}}\n| name         = Tori Allen-Martin\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Victoria Allen-Martin\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1986|06|23|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| years_active = 2006 \u2013present\n| occupation   = Actress, director, singer\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n}}\n\n'''Victoria \"Tori\" Allen-Martin''' (born June 23, 1986) is an English actress, director, singer/songwriter and producer.\n\n==Career==\nAllen-Martin was born in [[New York City]] and raised in [[London]].\n\nShe is known for the television series [[Pure]] (2019) and has also taken leading roles in [[Unforgotten]] (2018) and [[London Kills]] (2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvwise.co.uk/2018/06/hugo-speer-sharon-small-bailey-patrick-tori-allen-martin-set-as-leads-in-london-kills/|title=Cast Introduction to London Kills, 25 November 2018|website=TV Wise}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 she founded and headed Interval Productions as its Creative Director. Interval Productions has produced eight musicals which include Streets which has was nominated Best New Musical. Allen-Martin together with co-writer Sarah Henley were also nominated for most promising new playwrights<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecockpit.org.uk/article/word_on_the_streets/|title=Word on the Streets|website=The Cockpit}}</ref>.\n\nAllen-Martin was shortlisted under the writers category for BBC New Talent Hotlist 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/new-talent-hotlist/hotlist/|title=BBC New Talent Shortlist 2017|website=BBC Media Centre}}</ref>.\n\n===Television===\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year \n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Unforgotten]] \n| Sandra Rayworth\n| TV Series 3\n|-\n| 2019\n| [[Pure]] \n| Libby\n| TV Series\n|-\n| 2019\n| [[London Kills]]\n| TDC Billie Fitzgerald\n| TV Series\n|- \n|}\n\n===Theatre===\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year \n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| Streets: A New Kind Of Musical \n| Co-writer and producer\n| [[Cockpit Theatre, Marylebone|Cockpit Theatre]] , [[Marylebone]] , [[London]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| Muted <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.londontheatre.co.uk/theatre-news/interviews/interview-with-tori-allen-martin-about-new-musical-muted-at-the-bunker/|title=Interview with Tori Allen-Martin about new musical Muted, 2 December 2016|website=London Theatre}}</ref>.\n| Co-writer and producer\n| Bunker Theatre, [[Southwark]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.toriallenmartin.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|9980586|Tori Allen-Martin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT: Allen-Martin, Tori}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English female singers]]\n[[Category:English musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{dablinks|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|British actor|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR}}\n| name         = Tori Allen-Martin\n| image        = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   = Victoria Allen-Martin\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1986|06|23|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| years_active = 2006 \u2013present\n| occupation   = Actress, director, singer\n| spouse       = \n| children     = \n}}\n\n'''Victoria \"Tori\" Allen-Martin'''(born June 23, 1986) is an English actress, director, singer/songwriter and producer.\n\n==Career==\nAllen-Martin was born in [[New York City]] and raised in [[London]].\n\nShe is known for the television series [[Pure]] (2019) and has also taken leading roles in [[Unforgotten]] (2018) and [[London Kills]] (2019) <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tvwise.co.uk/2018/06/hugo-speer-sharon-small-bailey-patrick-tori-allen-martin-set-as-leads-in-london-kills/|title=Cast Introduction to London Kills, 25 November 2018|website=TV Wise}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 she founded and headed Interval Productions as its Creative Director. Interval Productions has produced eight musicals which include Streets which has was nominated Best New Musical. Allen-Martin together with co-writer Sarah Henley were also nominated for most promising new playwrights<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecockpit.org.uk/article/word_on_the_streets/|title=Word on the Streets|website=The Cockpit}}</ref>.\n\nAllen-Martin was shortlisted under the writers category for BBC New Talent Hotlist 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/mediapacks/new-talent-hotlist/hotlist/|title=BBC New Talent Shortlist 2017|website=BBC Media Centre}}</ref>.\n\n===Television===\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year \n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Unforgotten]] \n| Sandra Rayworth\n| TV Series 3\n|-\n| 2019\n| [[Pure]] \n| Libby\n| TV Series\n|-\n| 2019\n| [[London Kills]]\n| TDC Billie Fitzgerald\n| TV Series\n|- \n|}\n\n===Theatre===\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year \n! Title\n! Role\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| Streets: A New Kind Of Musical \n| Co-writer and producer\n| [[Cockpit Theatre, Marylebone|Cockpit Theatre]] , [[Marylebone]] , [[London]]\n|-\n| 2017\n| Muted <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.londontheatre.co.uk/theatre-news/interviews/interview-with-tori-allen-martin-about-new-musical-muted-at-the-bunker/|title=Interview with Tori Allen-Martin about new musical Muted, 2 December 2016|website=London Theatre}}</ref>.\n| Co-writer and producer\n| Bunker Theatre, [[Southwark]]\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n\n* {{Official website|http://www.toriallenmartin.com}}\n* {{IMDb name|9980586|Tori Allen-Martin}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT: Allen-Martin, Tori}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English female singers]]\n[[Category:English musical theatre actresses]]\n[[Category:English stage actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Lettler", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixing space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tori_Allen-Martin"}
{"title_page": "Ceahl\u0103u, Neam\u021b", "text_new": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Neam\u021b\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Neam\u021b County\n|name=Ceahl\u0103u\n|image_map              = Ceahl\u0103u in the Neam\u021b County.svg\n|coordinates = {{coord|47|3|N|25|58|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Ceahl\u0103u''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Neam\u021b County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of three villages: Bistricioara, Ceahl\u0103u and P\u00e2r\u00e2ul Mare.\n\n==Attractions==\nIn addition to a respectable church at Bistricoara, the village of Ceahl\u0103u has a larger 19th century wooden church, with wild swirling spires similar to those at [[Curtea de Arge\u0219]] in [[Arge\u0219 County]].  The village of Ceahl\u0103u also features a handful of three and four-star guesthouses and a hotel facing the beautiful Bicaz Lake (''Lacul Bicaz'' or ''Lacul Izvorul Muntelui'', meaning \"Mountain Spring Lake\").  <br /><gallery>\nImage:Satul Ceahlau Old Castle.jpg|The Old Princely Castle at Ceahl\u0103u\nImage:Satul Ceahlau Biserica.jpg|19th century church\n</gallery>\nIn addition to a little local general store, the village offers an ethnographic museum, and the remains of a princely castle just up behind the museum.  <br />\nLodging at Ceahl\u0103u is a reasonable alternative to the higher prices of the resort community of [[Dur\u0103u]] further up the river.\n\n==Geography==\nCeahl\u0103u is on the edge of the [[Ceahl\u0103u Massif]] portion of the [[carpathian mountains|Eastern Carpathian Mountains]]. The village itself runs along the Hermitage Brook (''p\u00e2r\u00e2ul Schitu''), and includes a small portion on the north-west side of the river along Mountain Spring Lake.\n\n==Ceahl\u0103u commune==\nCeahl\u0103u commune is made up of three main villages, that of Ceahl\u0103u, along with Bistricioara on the main road from Piatra Neam\u0163, and P\u00e2r\u00e2ul Mare (\"Big Stream\"). All of these villages are sited in the mountains, situated along the main watercourses which flow out of the surrounding peaks and ranges.\n\n===Ceahl\u0103u Village===\nThe actual village of Ceahl\u0103u is the seat of local government for the wider eponymous township, with about 1500 villagers, mostly along the P\u00e2r\u00e2ul Schit (\"Hermitage Stream\") (named for the original hermitage in Dur\u0103u upstream) which runs through the village centre.  The settlement here was originally named ''satul Schit'' (\"Hermitage Village\").\n\n===Bistricioara===\nThe nearby village of Bistricioara is on the main road, the national highway DN15 where it intersects with the DN155F, which runs along the lake, up through Ceahl\u0103u, and then up to the Dur\u0103u resort.   With about 800 inhabitants, Bistricioara is spread across the alluvial soils of the lower river of the same name, just before it flows into Mountain Spring Lake (also known as Lake Bicaz).\n\n===P\u00e2r\u00e2ul Mare===\nA newer development along the shores of the lake (which was man-made by damming the river in the 1950s to power a hydroelectric plant), 140 people enjoy excellent lake views, also along the P\u00e2r\u00e2ul Mare river.\n{{Neam\u0163 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ceahlau, Neamt}}\n[[Category:Communes in Neam\u021b County]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Romanian subdivision\n|type                   = commune\n|county                 = Neam\u021b\n|population_total       = auto\n|map_caption            = Location in Neam\u021b County\n|name=Ceahl\u0103u\n|image_map=\n|coordinates = {{coord|47|3|N|25|58|E|region:RO|display=it}}\n}}\n'''Ceahl\u0103u''' is a [[Commune in Romania|commune]] in [[Neam\u021b County]], [[Romania]]. It is composed of three villages: Bistricioara, Ceahl\u0103u and P\u00e2r\u00e2ul Mare.\n\n==Attractions==\nIn addition to a respectable church at Bistricoara, the village of Ceahl\u0103u has a larger 19th century wooden church, with wild swirling spires similar to those at [[Curtea de Arge\u0219]] in [[Arge\u0219 County]].  The village of Ceahl\u0103u also features a handful of three and four-star guesthouses and a hotel facing the beautiful Bicaz Lake (''Lacul Bicaz'' or ''Lacul Izvorul Muntelui'', meaning \"Mountain Spring Lake\").  <br /><gallery>\nImage:Satul Ceahlau Old Castle.jpg|The Old Princely Castle at Ceahl\u0103u\nImage:Satul Ceahlau Biserica.jpg|19th century church\n</gallery>\nIn addition to a little local general store, the village offers an ethnographic museum, and the remains of a princely castle just up behind the museum.  <br />\nLodging at Ceahl\u0103u is a reasonable alternative to the higher prices of the resort community of [[Dur\u0103u]] further up the river.\n\n==Geography==\nCeahl\u0103u is on the edge of the [[Ceahl\u0103u Massif]] portion of the [[carpathian mountains|Eastern Carpathian Mountains]]. The village itself runs along the Hermitage Brook (''p\u00e2r\u00e2ul Schitu''), and includes a small portion on the north-west side of the river along Mountain Spring Lake.\n\n==Ceahl\u0103u commune==\nCeahl\u0103u commune is made up of three main villages, that of Ceahl\u0103u, along with Bistricioara on the main road from Piatra Neam\u0163, and P\u00e2r\u00e2ul Mare (\"Big Stream\"). All of these villages are sited in the mountains, situated along the main watercourses which flow out of the surrounding peaks and ranges.\n\n===Ceahl\u0103u Village===\nThe actual village of Ceahl\u0103u is the seat of local government for the wider eponymous township, with about 1500 villagers, mostly along the P\u00e2r\u00e2ul Schit (\"Hermitage Stream\") (named for the original hermitage in Dur\u0103u upstream) which runs through the village centre.  The settlement here was originally named ''satul Schit'' (\"Hermitage Village\").\n\n===Bistricioara===\nThe nearby village of Bistricioara is on the main road, the national highway DN15 where it intersects with the DN155F, which runs along the lake, up through Ceahl\u0103u, and then up to the Dur\u0103u resort.   With about 800 inhabitants, Bistricioara is spread across the alluvial soils of the lower river of the same name, just before it flows into Mountain Spring Lake (also known as Lake Bicaz).\n\n===P\u00e2r\u00e2ul Mare===\nA newer development along the shores of the lake (which was man-made by damming the river in the 1950s to power a hydroelectric plant), 140 people enjoy excellent lake views, also along the P\u00e2r\u00e2ul Mare river.\n{{Neam\u0163 County}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ceahlau, Neamt}}\n[[Category:Communes in Neam\u021b County]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ceahl%C4%83u,_Neam%C8%9B"}
